div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

p.font:
The world is becoming more visual
and time poor. We are bombarded
with an ever increasing mountain
of information, and we are pressu-
red to spend less attention and
time on taking everything in. We
skim and scan our way through
documentation, missing a lot of
detail in the process.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.font:
WE DON'T HAVE
TIME TO READ

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

p.font:
Approximately 60% of us think
visually- we see a series of pictu-
res instead of words in our minds.
The human brain perceives diffe-
rences between images more
quickly, and ensureswe
remember graphics more easily
and thoroughly than written text.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

p.font:
Our visual IQ is increasingmore
rapidly than our general IQ - we
are getting better at recognizing
patterns. It is unclear though
whether this is the driving force
behind the rising popularity of
diagrams, or as a result of being
increasingly surrounded by
diagrams.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

p.font:
Imagine trying to convey an organizations management hierarchy with pure
text, or describe a complex business process with many decision points
without any supporting graphics. Even trying to explain a circuit board layout
or a simple room layout using only text sounds like a nightmare.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

p.font:
Businesses are quickly becoming technically,procedurally, and organizational-
ly more complex.Visualization is a great tool for communicating dense and
complex information quickly.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 60px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
Present training or on-boarding
material visually, in additional to
traditional reports and presenta-
tions. New employees will be
ready to be a productive part of
their teams more quickly, and
training courses will be more
successful.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
Use your employees' improved
spatial reasoning to solve a wide
range of problems and to design
better processes, structures, and
workflows to improve your com-
pany's productivity.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
Workplaces are becoming more
distributed, and teams are beco-
ming increasinglymulti-lingual.
Diagrams get around the language
barriers that are a big drain on
productivity.

switch.text: HOW CAN WE USE DIAGRAMS

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 45px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap; font-weight: bold;
display: inline-block; font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;
display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(187, 187, 187); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
Employees can understand diagrams more clearly, they can see dependencies
and relationships quickly, they have fewer questions, make fewer mistakes,
and are therefore more productive.

div.span:
HAVE ONE CENTRAL PLACE FOR
DOCUMENTATION

switch.text:
HAVE ONE CENTRAL PLACE FOR
DOCUMENTATION

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
To reap the maximum benefit, everyone should be able
to create and modify diagrams. Instead of only a few
people in an organization using a variety of specialized
graphics tools, choose one general tool and enable
everyone in the company to use it.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 15px; font-family: Verdana; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; white-space: nowrap;

div.p:
To cut down on duplication and wasted time, all
diagrams used in internal and external communications
must be developed and maintained in an intranet with all
other documentation, not statically hidden on local
computers and emailed around. This also improves
visibility and supports collaboration both within and
across teams and departments.
